# Hans-Hermann Hoppe

**Hans-Hermann Hoppe** (/ˈhɒpə/; German: [ˈhɔpə]; born 2 September 1949) is a [German-American](/German_Americans) academic affiliated with the [Austrian School](/Austrian_School) of economics, [anarcho-capitalism](/Anarcho-capitalism), [right-wing libertarianism](/Right-libertarianism), and a vocal critic of [democracy](/Democracy). From 1986 until his retirement in 2008, he held the position of professor of economics at the [University of Nevada, Las Vegas](/University_of_Nevada,_Las_Vegas) (UNLV). He is currently a senior fellow at the [Mises Institute](/Mises_Institute), a libertarian think tank. In 2006, he emigrated to Turkey, where he founded the [Property and Freedom Society](/Property_and_Freedom_Society). This organization has been noted for hosting speakers who have espoused [white nationalist](/White_nationalism) views at its conferences.

Hoppe's extensive critique of democracy is most famously articulated in his 2001 book, [Democracy: The God That Failed](/Democracy:_The_God_That_Failed). In this work, he advocates for exclusionary "covenant communities" designed for the "purpose of protecting family and kin." A particular section of the book, which argued for the exclusion of democrats and homosexuals from society, significantly contributed to Hoppe's visibility and appeal within the [far-right](/Far-right_politics).

Recognized as a protégé of [Murray Rothbard](/Murray_Rothbard), Hoppe was established at UNLV by Rothbard. During his tenure at UNLV, a 2004 incident involving a student's complaint about Hoppe's lecture comments regarding homosexuals and [time preference](/Time_preference) led to a university investigation. While the university initially issued a non-disciplinary letter to Hoppe, it was later withdrawn amidst controversy concerning [academic freedom](/Academic_freedom).

## Early life and education

Born in [Peine](/Peine), [West Germany](/West_Germany), on 2 September 1949, Hans-Hermann Hoppe's family had settled there in 1946 after fleeing [East Elbia](/East_Elbia), a region that fell under Soviet occupation following World War II. Hoppe has spoken of the lasting trauma caused by the expropriation of his mother's family, who were East Elbean [Junkers](/Junker), and has indicated he was raised with a [Protestant ethic](/Protestant_ethic).

His undergraduate studies were completed at [Saarland University](/Saarland_University). He subsequently earned his MA and PhD degrees in Philosophy from [Goethe University Frankfurt](/Goethe_University_Frankfurt). While studying there, he was a student of [Jürgen Habermas](/J%C3%BCrgen_Habermas), a prominent post-World War II German intellectual. However, Hoppe eventually rejected Habermas's ideas and, more broadly, European leftist thought.

From 1976 to 1978, Hoppe held a post-doctoral fellowship at the [University of Michigan](/University_of_Michigan) in [Ann Arbor](/Ann_Arbor,_Michigan). He later obtained his [habilitation](/Habilitation) in Foundations of Sociology and Economics from the University of Frankfurt in 1981.

## Career

Hoppe lectured in West Germany and Italy between 1981 and 1985. In 1986, he relocated to the United States, facilitated by [Murray Rothbard](/Murray_Rothbard) and a scholarship from the [Center for Libertarian Studies](/Center_for_Libertarian_Studies). Rothbard also played a key role in securing Hoppe a professorship at the [University of Nevada, Las Vegas](/University_of_Nevada,_Las_Vegas). He taught in the School of Business at UNLV from 1986 until his retirement in 2008. He is a Distinguished Fellow at the [Mises Institute](/Mises_Institute), a libertarian think tank responsible for publishing a significant portion of his work, and previously served as editor for several of its periodicals.

Hoppe frequently referred to Rothbard as his "principal teacher, mentor and master." He described their relationship as one of close collaboration, stating he was "working and living side-by-side with him, in constant and immediate personal contact," and considered Rothbard his "dearest fatherly friend" from 1985 until Rothbard's death in 1995.

### Mises Institute and John Randolph Club

The [Mises Institute](/Mises_Institute) was established in 1982 by [Lew Rockwell](/Lew_Rockwell), [Burton Blumert](/Burton_Blumert), and Murray Rothbard, following a schism between Rothbard and the [Cato Institute](/Cato_Institute), an organization Rothbard had co-founded. After Rothbard's passing in 1996, Hoppe emerged as a leading figure advocating for [anarcho-capitalism](/Anarcho-capitalism) within the Mises Institute.

Hoppe was also involved with the [John Randolph Club](/John_Randolph_Club), a coalition of [paleolibertarians](/Paleolibertarianism) and [paleoconservatives](/Paleoconservatism) organized by Rothbard and associated with the [Rockford Institute](/Rockford_Institute). During the 1990s, the club was known for promoting [secessionist](/Secession) and [neo-Confederate](/Neo-Confederates) viewpoints.

### Property and Freedom Society

In 2006, Hoppe founded The Property and Freedom Society (PFS), which convenes annual conferences in [Bodrum, Turkey](/Bodrum,_Turkey). The PFS, along with the Mises Institute, is seen as presenting a [paleolibertarian](/Paleolibertarianism) challenge to organizations like the [Mont Pelerin Society](/Mont_Pelerin_Society) and the [Atlas Network](/Atlas_Network). The PFS conferences have attracted figures from the [European New Right](/European_New_Right) and the American [alt-right](/Alt-right). Quinn Slobodian and Dieter Plehwe have characterized Hoppe as a "racialist right-wing libertarian," and Slobodian notes that the PFS has hosted former members of the [John Randolph Club](/John_Randolph_Club) alongside "new advocates of stateless libertarianism and racial secession."

Reflecting on the PFS's objectives in 2011, Hoppe stated: "On the one hand, positively, it was to explain and elucidate the legal, economic, cognitive and cultural requirements and features of a free, state-less natural order. On the other hand, negatively, it was to unmask the State and showcase it for what it really is: an institution run by gangs of murderers, plunderers and thieves, surrounded by willing executioners, propagandists, sycophants, crooks, liars, clowns, charlatans, dupes and useful idiots – an institution that dirties and taints everything it touches."

In 2016, Hoppe faced criticism for inviting speakers such as [white nationalist](/White_nationalist) [Jared Taylor](/Jared_Taylor) and [neo-Nazi](/Neo-Nazi) [Richard B. Spencer](/Richard_B._Spencer) to the PFS conference, where venture capitalist [Peter Thiel](/Peter_Thiel) also spoke. The Southern Poverty Law Center commented in 2016 that "in Hoppe one can see the connection between the ultra-Libertarians and white nationalists." In 2017, *[Intelligencer](/Intelligencer_(website))* described the annual PFS meeting as "Davos, but for racists." Quinn Slobodian, writing in 2023, observed that "prophets of racial and social breakdown share the stage with investment advisors and financial consultants" at these conferences.

## Views

### On democracy

Hoppe's 2001 book, [Democracy: The God That Failed](/Democracy:_The_God_That_Failed), posits that democracy is a catalyst for civilizational decline. The book argues against [universal suffrage](/Universal_suffrage) and expresses support for "natural elites." Hoppe attributes various social and economic problems to democratic governance, citing the influence of pressure groups seeking increased government spending and regulation. He proposes [secession](/Secession), governmental decentralization, and "complete freedom of contract, occupation, trade and migration" as alternatives. Hoppe contends that monarchy, in his view, would better preserve individual liberty than democracy. The book's arguments, particularly its call for the exclusion of political opponents, helped popularize Hoppe among the [far-right](/Far-right_politics).

Janek Wasserman suggests that Hoppe has "reimagined the Austrian legacy as one of authoritarianism, conservatism, antidemocracy, and anti-Enlightenment." [Steven Horwitz](/Steven_Horwitz), a colleague of Hoppe's at the Mises Institute, described the approach of Hoppe and [Joseph Salerno](/Joseph_T._Salerno) as "a fascist fist in a libertarian glove." The political scientist George Hawley identifies Hoppe as potentially "the most important bridge between libertarianism and the Alt-Right," noting Hoppe's assertion that libertarians must embrace being "radical conservatives" and must support a right to [discrimination](/Discrimination), including on the basis of [race](/Racial_discrimination).

Wasserman states that Hoppe believes the achievements of the [fin-de-siècle](/Fin-de-siecle) era and the Austrian School stemmed not from liberal dominance or cosmopolitan values, but from the [ancien régime](/Ancien_Régime) and its restrictive social order. In a 2013 statement, Hoppe argued that democracy leads to the erosion of the concept of beauty and universal aesthetic standards, being "swamped and submerged by so-called '[modern art](/Modern_art)'."

[Walter Block](/Walter_Block), a fellow Mises Institute scholar, reviewed *Democracy: The God That Failed*, acknowledging that Hoppe's arguments illuminated various historical phenomena, including wars, poverty, inflation, interest rates, and crime. Block noted Hoppe's concession that contemporary democracies are more prosperous than historical monarchies, but suggested Hoppe believes that if nobles and kings were to replace current political leaders, their long-term perspective on national well-being could lead to improvements. Block did, however, express minor reservations regarding Hoppe's theses on [time preferences](/Time_preference), immigration, and the perceived divergence between libertarianism and conservatism.

Alberto Benegas-Lynch Jr., an economics professor at the [University of Buenos Aires](/University_of_Buenos_Aires) with ties to the libertarian [Cato Institute](/Cato_Institute), challenged Hoppe's preference for monarchy over democracy, presenting data indicating that modern monarchies are generally less affluent than modern democracies. Hoppe countered that comparing predominantly African monarchies with predominantly European democracies could create a distorted perspective.

When questioned by [The Intercept](/The_Intercept) in 2021 about his ideas being incorporated into far-right [internet memes](/Internet_meme) that endorse political assassination, Hoppe dismissed the question as uninformed. He stated, "I have been an intellectual champion of private property right, free markets, freedom of contract and association, and peace," adding, "What do I know? There are lots of crazy people out there!"

### Covenant communities and discrimination

In *Democracy: The God That Failed*, Hoppe advocates for the right of property owners to establish communities with exclusive admission criteria. He describes a society composed of "[covenant communities](/Covenant_(law))" whose residents adhere to a shared agreement defining the community's nature. Hoppe argues these communities should possess the right to engage in certain forms of discrimination, including the physical separation of individuals whose lifestyles are perceived as incompatible with the community's norms. He writes, "There would be little or no 'tolerance' and 'openmindedness' so dear to [left-libertarians](/Left-libertarianism). Instead, one would be on the right path toward restoring the freedom of association and exclusion implied in the institution of [private property](/Private_property)."

Hoppe elaborates: "In a covenant concluded among proprietor and community tenants for the purpose of protecting their private property, no such thing as a right to free (unlimited) speech exists, ... naturally no one is permitted to advocate ideas contrary to the very purpose of the covenant of preserving and protecting private property, such as democracy and communism. There can be no tolerance toward democrats and communists in a libertarian social order. They will have to be physically separated and expelled from society. Likewise, in a covenant founded for the purpose of protecting family and kin, there can be no tolerance toward those habitually promoting lifestyles incompatible with this goal. They – the advocates of alternative, non-family and kin-centered lifestyles such as, for instance, individual hedonism, parasitism, nature-environment worship, homosexuality, or communism – will have to be physically removed from society, too, if one is to maintain a libertarian order."

Martin Snyder of the [American Association of University Professors](/American_Association_of_University_Professors) commented that Hoppe's statements evoke memories of segregation, apartheid, internment facilities, and concentration camps, and the associated symbols of persecution. [Walter Block](/Walter_Block) described Hoppe's call for the exclusion of homosexuals and others from polite society as "stark," "well written," and "radical," but also "exceedingly difficult to reconcile with libertarianism." Phillip Magness has argued that Hoppe's conservative cultural views are not derived from Misesian economics but from other right-wing political traditions and potentially the Frankfurt School.

### Support for immigration restrictions

Despite identifying as an anarcho-capitalist who advocates for the abolition of the nation-state, Hoppe has drawn criticism for his support of state enforcement of [immigration laws](/Immigration_law), a stance seen by some as contradictory to libertarian and anarcho-capitalist principles. Hoppe argues that as long as states exist, they should implement immigration restrictions. He equates unrestricted immigration with "forced integration," asserting it infringes upon the rights of native populations. He contends that in a system of privately owned land, immigration would naturally be regulated by the consent of property owners, not unimpeded.

[Walter Block](/Walter_Block), a colleague at the Mises Institute, has labeled Hoppe an "anti-open immigration activist." Block notes that Hoppe argues that while the state unjustly confiscates property through taxation, it further exacerbates this injustice by allowing immigrants to utilize public property, thereby infringing on the original owners' rights. However, Block disputes Hoppe's position, deeming it inconsistent with libertarianism. Block posits that Hoppe's reasoning could justify other unlibertarian laws, such as those regulating prostitution or drug use, by claiming that property owners might object to such activities on their land. Simon Guenzl, writing for *Libertarian Papers*, argues that supporting state intervention in immigration is incompatible with Rothbardian and Hoppean libertarian anarchism, as well as the broader strategy of consistently advocating for the reduction of state power.

Regarding specific immigration policies, Hoppe suggested that immigrants should demonstrate English proficiency, possess "superior (above-average) intellectual performance and character structure," and adhere to a "compatible system of values." He predicted this would foster a "systematic pro-European immigration bias." Jacob Hornberger of the Future of Freedom Foundation criticized Hoppe's proposed immigration criteria, suggesting it would likely discriminate against Latin American immigrants in the United States.

### Remarks about homosexuals and academic investigation

Hoppe's public statements and writings concerning [race](/Race_(human_categorization)) and [homosexuality](/Homosexuality) have generated significant controversy among both his libertarian peers and his colleagues at UNLV. Following a lecture on [time preference](/Time_preference) on 4 March 2004, a student formally complained that Hoppe had created a hostile classroom environment. The student alleged that Hoppe asserted homosexuals were generally more prone to shortsightedness in economic planning than heterosexuals, partly due to not having children. Hoppe also reportedly suggested that the homosexuality of [John Maynard Keynes](/John_Maynard_Keynes) might have influenced his economic theories, which Hoppe opposed. Hoppe further remarked that very young and very old individuals, as well as childless couples, were less likely to engage in long-term planning. He told a reporter that these comments constituted only 90 seconds of a 75-minute lecture, no students had questioned them at the time, and he had not received prior complaints in 18 years of delivering the lecture. The university requested an apology, which Hoppe delivered, likening his generalizations to national culinary habits. The student, however, felt Hoppe was not taking the complaint seriously and filed a formal grievance. Hoppe maintained he was the victim in the situation and suggested the student needed to "grow up."

An investigation ensued, culminating in a non-disciplinary letter of instruction from the university's provost, [Raymond W. Alden III](/Raymond_W._Alden_III), on 9 February 2005. The letter concluded that Hoppe had "created a hostile or intimidating educational environment in violation of the University's policies regarding discrimination as to sexual orientation." Alden instructed Hoppe to "cease mischaracterizing opinion as objective fact," noting that Hoppe's opinions were not supported by peer-reviewed academic literature.

Hoppe appealed the decision, alleging the university had "blatantly violated its contractual obligations" and engaged in "frivolous interference with my right to academic freedom." He was represented by the [American Civil Liberties Union](/American_Civil_Liberties_Union), which threatened legal action. The Nevada ACLU executive director stated that while they did not endorse Hoppe's theories or understand why some students found them offensive, academic freedom must protect professors' rights to present scholarly ideas relevant to their curriculum. The case gained significant attention from [Fox News](/Fox_News), various blogs, and libertarian activists who launched campaigns to contact the university. The university faced two weeks of negative publicity, and the Interim Chancellor of the [Nevada System of Higher Education](/Nevada_System_of_Higher_Education), [Jim Rogers](/James_E._Rogers_(attorney)), expressed concerns about potential infringements on free speech.

Jim Rogers denied Hoppe's request for a one-year paid sabbatical. On 18 February 2005, UNLV President [Carol Harter](/Carol_Harter) reviewed Hoppe's appeal and decided that his views, however controversial or unconventional, should not result in disciplinary action. She dismissed the discrimination complaint and ordered the non-disciplinary letter to be removed from Hoppe's personnel file, stating, "In the balance between freedoms and responsibilities, and where there may be ambiguity between the two, academic freedom must, in the end, be foremost."

Hoppe later chronicled the incident and the UNLV investigation in an article titled "My Battle With the Thought Police." Martin Snyder of the [American Association of University Professors](/American_Association_of_University_Professors) commented that Hoppe should not be "punished for freely expressing his opinions."

The Hoppe incident, alongside controversies involving remarks by [Harvard University](/Harvard_University) President [Lawrence Summers](/Lawrence_Summers), prompted UNLV to host a conference on academic freedom in October 2005. In 2009, UNLV proposed a new policy encouraging the reporting of bias incidents, which drew criticism from the Nevada ACLU and some faculty members who viewed it as a potential threat to academic freedom, recalling the Hoppe case.

### Argumentation ethics

In the September 1988 issue of *Liberty* magazine, Hoppe introduced a theory he named argumentation ethics, an attempt to establish an [a priori](/A_priori_and_a_posteriori) and [value-neutral](/Value_judgment) foundation for libertarian ethics. Hoppe asserted that any argument contradicting libertarian principles is logically incoherent. He posited that engaging in an argument implicitly assumes certain norms, including a prohibition against the initiation of violence. Hoppe extrapolated this to political life, arguing that these argumentation norms should universally apply. He claimed that only anarcho-capitalist libertarianism, with its [non-aggression principle](/Non-aggression_principle), prohibits the initiation of aggressive violence, rendering any argument for alternative political philosophies logically flawed.

*Liberty* published responses from ten libertarians in its subsequent issue, followed by a rejoinder from Hoppe. [Murray Rothbard](/Murray_Rothbard), a friend and mentor to Hoppe, praised the theory as "a dazzling breakthrough for political philosophy in general and for libertarianism in particular," suggesting it transcended the "famous [is/ought](/Is/ought), [fact/value](/Fact%E2%80%93value_distinction) dichotomy." However, the majority of surveyed colleagues rejected Hoppe's theory, which Hoppe dismissed as [utilitarianism](/Utilitarianism).

Roderick T. Long, a Senior Fellow at the Mises Institute, argued that Hoppe's a priori formulation of libertarianism conflicted with the foundational principles of Misesean [praxeology](/Praxeology), questioning how practical requirements could be justified independently of means-end structures. Libertarian philosopher [Jason Brennan](/Jason_Brennan) rejected Hoppe's argument, stating it "illicitly conflates a [liberty right with a claim right](/Claim_rights_and_liberty_rights)." J. Mikael Olsson argued that Hoppe failed to provide non-circular reasons for prioritizing consensual argument over subjective preferences, suggesting the theory relies on unproven intuitions. Commentators have noted that Hoppe's [original appropriation](/Original_appropriation) theory, initially leaning towards the [labor theory of property](/Labor_theory_of_property), later shifted towards the [first possession theory of property](/First_possession_theory_of_property).

### Influence

Hoppe has been cited as an influence by [neoreactionary](/Neoreactionary) [monarchist](/Monarchism) blogger [Curtis Yarvin](/Curtis_Yarvin), also known as Mencius Moldbug. Argentinian President [Javier Milei](/Javier_Milei) has identified Hoppe as a major influence and has recommended his bibliography, despite recent ideological disagreements concerning Milei's administration and the practical application of libertarian principles within a democratic system.

## Personal life

Hoppe resides in Turkey with his wife, Gülçin Imre Hoppe, who is also an Austrian School economist and a hotelier. The Property and Freedom Society conferences are held at their family-owned hotel, the Karia Princess, in [Bodrum](/Bodrum). As of 2024, their extended family includes four children and seven grandchildren.

